ity of California.|ref=<ref name=\"alumni\">{{cite news|title=Lowell Class of '62 reclaims building for reunion|url=http://www.sfgate.com/default/article/Lowell-Class-of-62-reclaims-building-for-reunion-3588955.php|newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle|date=May 26, 2012 | accessdate=June 12, 2013| quote=Graduates who became well-known politicians, judges, artists, clothiers, financiers, philanthropists and cultural fixtures were Cyril Magnin, Class of 1918, Edmund (Pat) Brown, '23, William Hewlett, '30, Carol Channing, '38 Richard Diebenkorn, '39, Pierre Salinger, '41, Art Hoppe, '42, Don Fisher, '46, Warren Hellman, '51, Richard Blum, '53, Stephen Breyer, '55, Charles Breyer, '59, Mark Buell and Susie Tompkins, both '60, and Sydney Goldstein, '62.}}</ref><ref>Groves, Martha. [http://articles.latimes.com/1990-05-27/business/fi-426_1_richard-blum/2 \"The Man Behind the Woman Who Would Be Governor : Politics: Dianne Feinstein's husband, Richard Blum, is a shrewd businessman, a friend of the famous, with a 'Lt. Columbo style' and a passion for distance running and Tibetan treks.\"], ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', May 27, 1990. Accessed June 12, 2013. \"A lifelong San Franciscan, Blum was brought up in well-to-do circumstances.... Blum attended San Rafael Military Academy for a year, then went to prestigious Lowell High School.\"</ref>}}\n{{Alum|name=[[Stephen Breyer]]|year=1955|nota=Associate Justice in the [[United States Supreme Court]].|ref=<ref name=\"alumni\" /><ref>[https://www.pbs.org/wnet/supremecourt/future/robes_breyer.html Stephen Gerald Breyer], ''The Future of the Court''. Accessed June 12, 2013. \"He graduated from San Francisco's prestigious Lowell High School in 1955 and went on to Stanford University, where he majored in philosophy and received his A.B. in 1959.\"</ref>}}\n{{Alum|name=[[William Ware Theiss]]|year= 1948|nota=Academy Award nominated Costume Designer for movies and TV, including ''[[Star Trek]]''.|ref=<ref>{{cite book|title=Lowell High School \u2013 Red and White Yearbook (San Francisco, CA) \u2013 Class of 1956|year=1956|url=http://www.e-yearbook.com/yearbooks/Lowell_High_School_Red_White_Yearbook/1956/Page_193.html}}</ref> }}\n{{Alum|name=[[Tom Meschery]]|year=1957|nota=Played in the [[NBA]] for the [[Golden State Warriors|Warriors]] and [[Seattle SuperSonics|SuperSonics]], 1961\u20131971.|ref=<ref name=AlumniAssociation />}}\n{{Alum|name=[[Charles R. Breyer]]|year=1959|nota=[[United States federal judge|Senior United States District Judge]] for the [[United States District Court for the Northern District of California]].|ref=<ref name=\"alumni\" />}}\n{{Alum|name=[[Susie Tompkins Buell]]|year=1960|nota=Entrepreneur and liberal political donor associated with the [[Democracy Alliance]].|ref=<ref name=\"alumni\" />}}\n{{Alum|name=[[Julia Chang Bloch]]|year=1960|nota=[[U.S. Ambassador]] to [[Nepal]].}}\n{{Alum|name=[[Steve Silver]]|year=1962|nota=Creator of [[Beach Blanket Babylon]].|ref=<ref name=\"alumni\" />}}\n{{Alum|name=[[Eric Albronda]]|year=1963|nota=Founding member of the band [[Blue Cheer]], often considered to be the first heavy metal band|ref=<ref>[http://www.classmates.com/yearbooks/Lowell-High-School/119656 Lowell High School year book 1962]</ref>}}\n{{Alum|name=[[Richard Levin]]|year=1964|nota=President of [[Yale University]] from 1993 to 2013.|ref=<ref name=AlumniAssociation />}}\n{{Alum|name=[[Dennis Marcellino]]|year=1965|nota=Former member of [[Sly & The Family Stone]], The [[Elvin Bishop]] Group, [[Rubicon (US band)|Rubicon]], and The Tokens ([[The Lion Sleeps Tonight]])|ref=<ref>[http://www.dennismarcellino.com/musicroots.html Music Roots], Dennis Marcellino. Accessed June 12, 2013. \"Because of the changing tastes in popular music in America, in 1962 he switched to saxophone and became a vocalist/front man in his first rock band, The Spotliters, whom he worked with until 1965, when he also got married the month after he graduated from Lowell High School.\"</ref>}}\n{{Alum|name=[[Michael Bortin]]|year=1966|nota=Member of the [[Symbionese Liberation Army]].|ref=<ref name=\"Bay Area's roll call of fame\">[http://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Bay-Area-s-roll-call-of-fame-3296424.php#photo-2443624 \"Bay Area's roll call of fame\"], [[SFGate.com]], June 2, 2009.</ref>}}\n{{Alum|name=[[Stephen Suleyman Schwartz]]|year=1966|nota=Journalist and author.|ref=<ref>Yolandha, Friska. [http://www.republika.co.id/berita/dunia-islam/mualaf/12/01/18/lxywla-stephen-suleyman-schwartz-dari-komunis-menjadi-muslim-bag-1 \"Stephen Suleyman Schwartz: Dari Komunis Menjadi Muslim (Bag 1)\"], ''[[Republika (Indonesian newspaper)]]'', January 18, 2012. Accessed June 12, 2013. \"Ayahnya berjualan buku dan ibunya adalah pekerja sosial. Keluarganya hijrah ke San Francisco, ketika dirinya masih kecil. Di kota itu, Schwartz menempuh pendidikan pada Lowell High School.\"</ref>}}\n{{Alum|name=[[Linda Tillery]]|year=1966|nota=Singer, percussionist, music arranger, record producer; founder of The Cultural Heritage Choir.|ref=<ref name=\"Zane\">{{cite news |last=Zane |first=Maitland |date=October 24, 1997 |title=African-American History Provides Melody for Oakland Singer|newspaper=The San Francisco Chronicle |location=San Francisco, CA |edition=Final|page=EB 3|quote=\"Tillery's singing career began at Lowell High....'When I graduated in '66' ....\"}}</ref>}}\n{{Alum|name=[[Charles H. Ferguson]]|year=1972|nota=Software entrepreneur; Writer; Filmmaker. Film ''[[Inside Job (2010 film)|Inside Job]]'' won 2011 best documentary [[Academy Award]].}}<ref>{{cite news|author=Terence Abad |title=Caught in the Headlines |date=Winter 2008 |page=2 |work=Lowell Alumni Association |format=[[PDF]] |url=http://www.lowellalumni.org/download/laa_winter08.pdf |accessdate=2011-04-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719153310/http://www.lowellalumni.org/download/laa_winter08.pdf |archivedate=2011-07-19 }}</ref>\n{{Alum|name=[[John Roos]]|year=1973|nota=Attorney & U.S. Ambassador to Japan.|ref=<ref>[http://asiasociety.org/northern-california/events/john-v-roos-us-ambassador-japan John V. Roos, US Ambassador to Japan], [[Asia Society]]. Accessed June 12, 2013. \"Roos grew up in San Francisco and graduated from Lowell High School in 1973 before attending college at Stanford University, from which he graduated Phi Beta Kappa with honors and distinction in 1977.\"</ref>}}\n{{Alum|name=[[Larry Baer]]|year=1975|nota=President of the [[San Francisco Giants]] MLB team.|ref=<ref>[http://sanfrancisco.giants.mlb.com/sf/team/frontoffice_bios/baer_larry.jsp SF Giants President and Chief Operating Officer, Laurence M. Baer], [[San Francisco Giants]]. Accessed June 12, 2013. \"The San Francisco Lowell High School graduate was the driving force behind every phase of the ballpark project...\"</ref><ref>[http://news.sfsu.edu/giants-president-and-ceo-larry-baer-deliver-sf-state-commencement-keynote \"Giants President and CEO Larry Baer to deliver SF State Commencement keynote\"], [[San Francisco State University]], April 2, 2013. Accessed June 12, 2013. \"Baer attended nearby San Francisco Lowell High School, and said that SF State continues to be the influential community partner that he remembers from his youth in the public schools.\"</ref>}}\n{{Alum|name=[[John D. Trasvi\u00f1a]]|year=1976|nota=President of [[MALDEF]], [[U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development|HUD]] Assistant Secretary of [[Fair housing|Fair Housing]] and Equal Opportunity.|ref=<ref>[http://www.lowellalumni.org/article_s07_socal_reunion.shtml Lowell Alumni Southern California Luncheon 4/9/05] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071030010931/http://www.lowellalumni.org/article_s07_socal_reunion.shtml |date=2007-10-30 }} (retrieved May 23, 2009).</ref>}}\n{{Alum|name=[[Gill Byrd]]|year=1978|nota=Played in the [[NFL]] for the [[San Diego Chargers]], 1983\u20131992.|ref=<ref>Nightengale, Bob. [http://articles.latimes.com/1989-09-08/sports/sp-1719_1_gill-byrd \"HE COMES TO PRAY : Gill Byrd Wishes Teammates Would Understand Why God, Not Football, Comes First\"], ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', September 8, 1989. Accessed June 12, 2013. \"Byrd's skin darkens with embarrassment as he recall his days at Lowell High School in San Francisco.\"</ref>}}\n{{Alum|name=[[Eric Allin Cornell]]|year=1980|nota=Nobel Prize in Physics in 2001.|ref=<ref>[https://www.nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/physics/laureates/2001/cornell-autobio.html Eric A. Cornell Autobiography], [[Nobel Prize]]. Accessed June 12, 2013. \"Just before my final year of high school, my brother, sister and I moved with my mother to San Francisco. I spent my last year of high school there, at Lowell High School. Lowell High was a so-called 'magnet school,' drawing academically inclined students from all over the city.\"</ref>}}\n{{Alum|name=[[Jennifer Egan]]|year=1980|nota=Novelist and short story writer.|ref=<ref>Ciabattari, Jane. [http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2010/06/29/jennifer-egan-interview-a-visit-from-the-goon-squad.html \"The Book on Aging Rockers\"], ''[[The Daily Beast]]'', June 29, 2010. Accessed June 12, 2013. \"After her parents were divorced and her mother remarried, she moved to San Francisco, where she attended Lowell High School and considered herself an 'unexceptional' student.\"</ref>}}\n{{Alum|name=[[Soji Kashiwagi]]|year=1980|nota=Playwright, Executive Producer for [[Grateful Crane Ensemble]] theatre organization.|ref=<ref>Kashiwagi, Soji. [http://www.discovernikkei.org/en/journal/2007/3/14/nihonmachi/ \"Nihonmachi: The Place to Be \"], Discover Nikkei, March 14, 2007. Accessed June 12, 2013. \"I attended Lowell High and San Francisco State University, but after school and on weekends the place to be for me was Nihonmachi.\"</ref>}}\n{{Alum|name=[[Naomi Wolf]]|year=1980|nota=[[Rhodes Scholar]], Writer.|ref=<ref name=AlumniAssociation />}}\n{{Alum|name=[[Benjamin Bratt]]|year=1982|nota=Movie and TV personality who starred in the television series, ''[[Law & Ord